# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: abandoned-pets
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] A major worldwide financial crisis centered in the United States took place in 2008.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The causes included excessive speculation on property values by both homeowners and financial institutions, leading to the 2000s United States housing bubble.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] This was exacerbated by predatory lending for subprime mortgages and by deficiencies in regulation.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Cash out refinancings had fueled an increase in consumption that could no longer be sustained when home prices declined.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The first phase of the crisis was the subprime mortgage crisis, which began in early 2007, as mortgage-backed securities (MBS) tied to U.S. real estate, and a vast web of derivatives linked to those MBS collapsed in value.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] A liquidity crisis spread to global institutions by mid-2007 and climaxed with the bankruptcy of Lehman Brothers in September 2008, which triggered a stock market crash and bank runs in several countries.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The crisis exacerbated the Great Recession, a global recession that began in late-2007, as well as the United States bear market of 2007–2009.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] It was also a contributor to the 2008–2011 Icelandic financial crisis and the euro area crisis.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] As the Federal Reserve ("Fed") lowered the federal funds rate from 2000 to 2003, institutions increasingly targeted low-income homebuyers, largely belonging to racial minorities, with high-risk loans; this development went unattended by regulators.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] As interest rates rose from 2004 to 2006, the cost of mortgages rose and the demand for housing fell; in early 2007, as more U.S. subprime mortgage holders began defaulting on their repayments, lenders went bankrupt, culminating in the bankruptcy of New Century Financial in April.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] As demand and prices continued to fall, the financial contagion spread to global credit markets by August 2007, and central banks began injecting liquidity.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In March 2008, Bear Stearns, the fifth-largest U.S. investment bank, was sold to JPMorgan Chase in a "fire sale" backed by Fed financing.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In response to the growing crisis, governments around the world deployed massive bailouts of financial institutions and used monetary policy and fiscal policies to prevent an economic collapse of the global financial system.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] By July 2008, Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, companies which together owned or guaranteed half of the U.S. housing market, verged on collapse; the Housing and Economic Recovery Act of 2008 enabled the federal government to seize them on September 7.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] On October 3, Congress passed the Emergency Economic Stabilization Act, authorizing the Treasury Department to purchase toxic assets and bank stocks through the $700 billion Troubled Asset Relief Program (TARP).
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Fed began a program of quantitative easing by buying treasury bonds and other assets, such as MBS, and the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act, signed in February 2009 by newly elected president Barack Obama, included a range of measures intended to preserve existing jobs and create new ones.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] These initiatives combined, coupled with actions taken in other countries, ended the worst of the Great Recession by mid-2009.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Assessments of the crisis's impact in the U.S. vary, but suggest that some 8.7 million jobs were lost, causing unemployment to rise from 5% in 2007 to a high of 10% in October 2009.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The percentage of citizens living in poverty rose from 12.5% in 2007 to 15.1% in 2010.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell by 53% between October 2007 and March 2009, and some estimates suggest that one in four households lost 75% or more of their net worth.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In 2010, the Dodd–Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act was passed, overhauling financial regulations.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] It was opposed by many Republicans, and it was weakened by the Economic Growth, Regulatory Relief, and Consumer Protection Act in 2018.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Basel III capital and liquidity standards were also adopted by countries around the world.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The crisis exacerbated the Great Recession, a global recession that began in mid-2007.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] It was among the five worst financial crises the world had experienced and led to a loss of more than $2 trillion from the global economy.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] U.S. home mortgage debt relative to GDP increased from an average of 46% during the 1990s to 73% during 2008, reaching $10.5 (~$15 trillion in 2024) trillion.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The increase in cash out refinancings, as home values rose, fueled an increase in consumption that could no longer be sustained when home prices declined.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Many financial institutions owned investments whose value was based on home mortgages such as mortgage-backed securities, or credit derivatives used to insure them against failure, which declined in value significantly.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The International Monetary Fund estimated that large U.S. and European banks lost more than $1 trillion on toxic assets and from bad loans from January 2007 to September 2009.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Lack of investor confidence in bank solvency and declines in credit availability led to plummeting stock and commodity prices in late 2008 and early 2009.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The crisis rapidly spread into a global economic shock, resulting in several bank failures.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Economies worldwide slowed during this period since credit tightened and international trade declined.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Housing markets suffered and unemployment soared, resulting in evictions and foreclosures.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] From its peak in the second quarter of 2007 at $61.4 trillion, household wealth in the United States fell $11 trillion, to $50.4 trillion by the end of the first quarter of 2009, resulting in a decline in consumption, then a decline in business investment.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In the fourth quarter of 2008, the quarter-over-quarter decline in real GDP in the U.S. was 8.4%.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The U.S. unemployment rate peaked at 11.0% in October 2009, the highest rate since 1983 and roughly twice the pre-crisis rate.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The average hours per work week declined to 33, the lowest level since the government began collecting the data in 1964.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The economic crisis started in the U.S. but spread to the rest of the world.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] U.S. consumption accounted for more than a third of the growth in global consumption between 2000 and 2007 and the rest of the world depended on the U.S. consumer as a source of demand.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Toxic securities were owned by corporate and institutional investors globally.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Derivatives such as credit default swaps also increased the linkage between large financial institutions.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The de-leveraging of financial institutions, as assets were sold to pay back obligations that could not be refinanced in frozen credit markets, further accelerated the solvency crisis and caused a decrease in international trade.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Reductions in the growth rates of developing countries were due to falls in trade, commodity prices, investment and remittances sent from migrant workers (example: Armenia).
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] States with fragile political systems feared that investors from Western states would withdraw their money because of the crisis.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In effect, the central banks went from being the "lender of last resort" to the "lender of only resort" for a significant portion of the economy.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In some cases the Fed was considered the "buyer of last resort".
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] During the fourth quarter of 2008, these central banks purchased US$2.5 trillion (~$3.57 trillion in 2024) of government debt and troubled private assets from banks.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] This was the largest liquidity injection into the credit market, and the largest monetary policy action in world history.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Federal Reserve created then-significant amounts of new currency as a method to combat the liquidity trap.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Bailouts came in the form of trillions of dollars of loans, asset purchases, guarantees, and direct spending.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Significant controversy accompanied the bailouts, such as in the case of the AIG bonus payments controversy, leading to the development of a variety of "decision making frameworks", to help balance competing policy interests during times of financial crisis.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Alistair Darling, the U.K.'s Chancellor of the Exchequer at the time of the crisis, stated in 2018 that Britain came within hours of "a breakdown of law and order" the day that Royal Bank of Scotland was bailed-out.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Instead of financing more domestic loans, some banks instead spent some of the stimulus money in more profitable areas such as investing in emerging markets and foreign currencies.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In July 2010, the Dodd–Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act was enacted in the United States to "promote the financial stability of the United States".
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Basel III capital and liquidity standards were adopted worldwide.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Since the 2008 financial crisis, consumer regulators in America have more closely supervised sellers of credit cards and home mortgages in order to deter anticompetitive practices that led to the crisis.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] At least two major reports on the causes of the crisis were produced by the U.S.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Congress: the Financial Crisis Inquiry Commission report, released January 2011, and a report by the United States Senate Homeland Security Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations entitled Wall Street and the Financial Crisis: Anatomy of a Financial Collapse, released April 2011.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In total, 47 bankers served jail time as a result of the crisis, over half of whom were from Iceland, where the crisis was the most severe and led to the collapse of all three major Icelandic banks.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In April 2012, Geir Haarde of Iceland became the only politician to be convicted as a result of the crisis.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In the aftermath of the crisis, U.S. authorities intensified enforcement actions against financial misconduct, including high-profile insider trading prosecutions such as that of Raj Rajaratnam, who was convicted in 2011.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Only one banker in the United States served jail time as a result of the crisis, Kareem Serageldin, a banker at Credit Suisse who was sentenced to 30 months in jail and returned $24.6 million in compensation for manipulating bond prices to hide $1 billion of losses.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] No individuals in the United Kingdom were convicted as a result of the crisis.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Goldman Sachs*, Goldman Sachs paid a $550 million civil penalty and acknowledged that its marketing materials for CDO contained incomplete information, settling securities fraud charges after allegedly anticipating the financial crisis and selling toxic investments to its clients.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] With fewer resources to risk in creative destruction, the number of patent applications was flat, compared to exponential increases in patent application in prior years.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Typical American families did not fare well, nor did the "wealthy-but-not-wealthiest" families just beneath the pyramid's top.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] However, half of the poorest families in the United States did not have wealth declines at all during the crisis because they generally did not own financial investments whose value could fluctuate.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Federal Reserve surveyed 4,000 households from 2007 to 2009, and found that the total wealth of 63% of all Americans declined in that period and 77% of the richest families had a decrease in total wealth, while only 50% of those on the bottom of the pyramid suffered a decrease.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The following is a timeline of the major events of the financial crisis, including government responses, and the subsequent economic recovery.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In the table, the names of emerging and developing economies are shown in boldface type, while the names of developed economies are in Roman (regular) type.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The expansion of central bank lending in response to the crisis was not confined to the Federal Reserve's provision of aid to individual financial institutions.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Federal Reserve has also conducted several innovative lending programs to improve liquidity and strengthen different financial institutions and markets, such as Freddie Mac and Fannie Mae.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In this case, the major problem in the market is the lack of free cash reserves and flows to secure the loans.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Federal Reserve took many steps to deal with financial market liquidity worries.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] One of these steps was a credit line for major traders, who act as the Fed's partners in open market activities.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Also, loan programs were set up to make the money market mutual funds and commercial paper market more flexible.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Also, the Term Asset-Backed Securities Loan Facility (TALF) was put in place thanks to a joint effort with the US Department of the Treasury.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] This plan made it easier for consumers and businesses to get credit by giving Americans who owned high-quality asset-backed securities more credit.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Before the crisis, the Federal Reserve's stocks of Treasury securities were sold to pay for the increase in credit.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] This method was meant to keep banks from trying to give out their extra savings, which could cause the federal funds rate to drop below where it was supposed to be.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] However, in October 2008, the Federal Reserve was granted the power to provide banks with interest payments on their surplus reserves.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] This created a motivation for banks to retain their reserves instead of disbursing them, thus reducing the need for the Federal Reserve to hedge its increased lending by decreases in alternative assets.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Money market funds also went through runs when people lost faith in the market.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] To keep it from getting worse, the Fed said it would give money to mutual fund companies.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Also, the Department of Treasury said that it would briefly cover the assets of the fund.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Both of these things helped get the fund market back to normal, which helped the commercial paper market, which most businesses use to run.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The FDIC also did several things, such as raising the insurance cap from $100,000 to $250,000, to boost customer trust.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] They engaged in quantitative easing, which added more than $4 trillion to the financial system and got banks to start lending again, both to each other and to people.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Many homeowners who were trying to keep their homes from going into default got housing credits.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p01] A package of policies was passed that let borrowers refinance their loans even though the value of their homes was less than what they still owed on their mortgages.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The relaxing of credit lending standards by investment banks and commercial banks allowed for a significant increase in subprime lending.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Subprime had not become less risky; Wall Street just accepted this higher risk.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Due to competition between mortgage lenders for revenue and market share, and when the supply of creditworthy borrowers was limited, mortgage lenders relaxed underwriting standards and originated riskier mortgages to less creditworthy borrowers.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In the view of some analysts, the relatively conservative government-sponsored enterprises (GSEs) policed mortgage originators and maintained relatively high underwriting standards prior to 2003.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p02] However, as market power shifted from securitizers to originators, and as intense competition from private securitizers undermined GSE power, mortgage standards declined and risky loans proliferated.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The riskiest loans were originated in 2004–2007, the years of the most intense competition between securitizers and the lowest market share for the GSEs.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The GSEs eventually relaxed their standards to try to catch up with the private banks.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Depending on how "subprime" mortgages are defined, they remained below 10% of all mortgage originations until 2004, when they rose to nearly 20% and remained there through the 2005–2006 peak of the United States housing bubble.
[src:abandoned-pets/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Although they concede that governmental policies had some role in causing the crisis, they contend that GSE loans performed better than loans securitized by private investment banks, and performed better than some loans originated by institutions that held loans in their own portfolios.
